{"title_page": "Ad-Rock", "text_new": "{{Other people|Adam Horovitz}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Ad-Rock\n| image           = Loz horo.png\n| image_size      = 250px\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Adam Keefe Horovitz\n| alias           = {{hlist|Ad-Rock|King Ad-Rock|Shadrach}}\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|mf=y|1966|10|31}}\n| birth_place     = [[New York City, New York]], U.S.\n| origin          =\n| instrument      = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|keyboards|bass|drums|[[E-mu SP-1200]]|turntables}}\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Rap rock]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]|[[hardcore punk]]|[[alternative hip hop]]}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Rapper|musician|songwriter|guitarist|actor}}\n| years_active    = 1982\u2013present\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Beastie Boys]]|[[BS 2000]]|[[Dead Fucking Last]]|[[The Young and the Useless]]}}\n| website         = {{URL|beastieboys.com}}\n| current_members = \n| past_members    = \n}}\n[[File:Beastie Boys Sonar 2007 Barcelona Catalonia.jpg|thumb|Ad-Rock with the Beastie Boys in [[Barcelona]], Spain on September 5, 2007.]]\n'''Adam Keefe Horovitz''' (born October 31, 1966),<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p50588|pure_url=yes}}|title=Ad-Rock biography|publisher=[[Allmusic]] [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref> better known as '''Ad-Rock''' or '''King Ad-Rock''', is an American rapper, guitarist and actor. He was a member of the [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] group [[Beastie Boys]]. He is married to musician and feminist activist [[Kathleen Hanna]].<ref name=married/>\n\n==Early life==\nHorovitz was born and raised on [[Park Avenue]], Manhattan, New York, the son of Doris (n\u00e9e Keefe) and playwright [[Israel Horovitz]].<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/73/Israel-Horovitz.html Israel Horovitz Biography (1939-)], Film Reference, accessed March 24, 2011.</ref> His sister is film producer [[Rachael Horovitz]]. His father is [[Jewish]], whereas his mother, who was of Irish descent, was [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wickedlocal.com/wakefield/x477566936|title=Israel Horovitz on art and religion|author=Susan Jacobs|work=Wakefield Observer}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/the_ticket/item/how_studio_exec-turned-producer_pitched_moneyball_20120216/|title=How studio exec-turned-producer pitched 'Moneyball' - The Ticket|work=Jewish Journal}}</ref> He was raised secular.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Nate |last=Bloom |authorlink=Nate Bloom |title=Jewish Stars 12/16 |publisher=[[Cleveland Jewish News]]|date=December 15, 2011|url=https://www.clevelandjewishnews.com/archives/jewish-stars/article_7be302da-267e-11e1-b2fe-001871e3ce6c.html|accessdate=|quote=His father, famous playwright Israel Horovitz, 72, said a few years ago that he regretted raising Adam secular}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHorovitz began his music career with a stint in the [[punk rock]] band [[The Young and the Useless]], who would often perform with Beastie Boys. In 1982, Beastie Boys guitarist John Berry quit and Horovitz replaced him. He was only 16 at the time.<ref>Diamond, Michael (1994), ''[[Some Old Bullshit]]'' album liner notes</ref> After Horovitz joined the band, Beastie Boys changed their sound, evolving from a [[hardcore punk]] band to a more hip-hop oriented group.  The band was signed to [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]], and released their debut album ''[[Licensed to Ill]]'' in 1986.  The album was a huge commercial success, and spawned six hit singles. Seven further albums followed, and by 2010 Beastie Boys had sold 22 million records in the United States alone, and 40&nbsp;million worldwide. In 2012, Beastie Boys were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].\n\nIn addition to his work with Beastie Boys, Horovitz also remixes numerous tracks for other artists under the alias 41 Small Stars.<ref>{{cite web|title=41 Small Stars|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/332355-41-Small-Stars|publisher=Discogs.com|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref> He plays bass in The Tender Moments, the backing band of New York-based [[cabaret]] performer [[Bridget Everett]].<ref name= \"bridget\">{{cite news |last=Arman |first=Marcus |url= http://www.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2012/11/30/bridget-everett-and-ad-rock-get-raunchy |title=Bridget Everett and Ad-Rock Get Raunchy |work=[[LA Weekly]] |date=2012-11-30 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nHorovitz has also acted in several motion pictures and television shows.  Some of his roles include Tim 'Chino' Doolan in ''[[Lost Angels]]'' (1989), Sam in ''[[Roadside Prophets]]'' (1992), Repulski in ''Godspeed'' (2007), Fletcher in ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]'' (2014), and Nick in ''[[Golden Exits]]'' (2017).\n\nIn 2020, he was featured in the documentary ''Have a Good Trip'' <ref>https://relix.com/news/detail/bill-kreutzmann-ad-rock-adam-scott-sarah-silverman-and-others-swap-stories-in-have-a-good-trip-adventures-in-psychedelics/ Relix</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the late 1980s, Horovitz was in a relationship with American actress [[Molly Ringwald]]. They met on the set of ''[[The Pick-up Artist (film)|The Pick-up Artist]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barshad|first1=Amos|title=Rude Boys|url=http://nymag.com/arts/popmusic/features/beastie-boys-2011-5/index4.html|accessdate=April 15, 2015|work=[[New York Magazine]]|date=April 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/the-secret-life-of-the-american-teenager/articles/molly-ringwalds-relationship-history-who-has-she-dated|title=Molly Ringwald's Relationship History: Who Has She Dated?|author=Mehera Bonner|work=Wetpaint}}</ref>\n\nHorovitz was married to actress [[Ione Skye]] from 1992 to 1995. They separated in 1995 and divorced in 1999. Since 1997 he has been involved with [[riot grrrl]] artist [[Kathleen Hanna]]; they married in 2006.<ref name=married /> Horovitz is featured prominently in ''[[The Punk Singer]]'', a 2013 documentary film about Hanna's life and career; he even shot a scene himself to show Hanna's distressed reaction to the medication she was taking against [[Lyme disease]].<ref name=EW>{{cite journal |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/03/12/sxsw-bikini-kill-kathleen-hanna-reveals-illness-in-new-doc-punk-singer/ |title=Bikini Kill's Kathleen Hanna reveals illness, reconfirms awesomeness in 'The Punk Singer' |journal=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 12, 2013 |last=Valby |first=Karen }}</ref> \n\nHorovitz began to wear a [[medical alert bracelet]] following the [[tonic\u2013clonic seizure]] he experienced in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2004/07/beastie-boys-twilight-brats/?page=1|title=Beastie Boys: Twilight of the Brats|work=Spin}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Horovitz purchased a house in [[South Pasadena, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amlu.com/2018/11/06/musician-adam-horovitz-of-beastie-boys-fame-buys-in-south-pasadena-at-1-7m/|title=Musician Adam Horovitz of Beastie Boys Fame Buys in South Pasadena at $1.7M|work=American Luxury}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Beastie Boys discography}}\n\n;with Beastie Boys \n* ''[[Licensed to Ill]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Paul's Boutique]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Check Your Head]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Ill Communication]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Hello Nasty]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[To the 5 Boroughs]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Mix-Up]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Hot Sauce Committee Part Two]]'' (2011)\n\n;with BS 2000 \n* ''[[BS 2000 (album)|BS 2000]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Simply Mortified]]'' (2000)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Lost Angels]]'' (1989) as Tim 'Chino' Doolan \n* ''[[Roadside Prophets]]'' (1992) as Sam\n* ''[[Who's the Man?]]'' (1993) as Bryant (cameo)\n* ''Godspeed'' (2007) as Repulski\n* ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]'' (2014) as Fletcher\n* ''[[Golden Exits]]'' (2017) as Nick\n* ''[[Beastie Boys Story]]'' (2020) as Himself\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=married>{{cite web|title='The Punk Singer' director on capturing the essence of Bikini Kill's Kathleen Hanna|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2013/09/03/the-punk-singer-poster|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|395259}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Beastie Boys}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ad-Rock}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Beastie Boys members]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:People with epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Rap rock musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Adam Horovitz}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Ad-Rock\n| image           = Loz horo.png\n| image_size      = 250px\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Adam Keefe Horovitz\n| alias           = {{hlist|Ad-Rock|King Ad-Rock|Shadrach}}\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|mf=y|1966|10|31}}\n| birth_place     = [[New York City, New York]], U.S.\n| origin          =\n| instrument      = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|keyboards|bass|drums|[[E-mu SP-1200]]|turntables}}\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Rap rock]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]|[[hardcore punk]]|[[alternative hip hop]]}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Rapper|musician|songwriter|guitarist|actor}}\n| years_active    = 1982\u2013present\n| label          