ew years ago that he regretted raising Adam secular}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHorovitz began his music career with a stint in the [[punk rock]] band [[The Young and the Useless]], who would often perform with Beastie Boys. In 1982, Beastie Boys guitarist John Berry quit and Horovitz replaced him. He was only 16 at the time.<ref>Diamond, Michael (1994), ''[[Some Old Bullshit]]'' album liner notes</ref> After Horovitz joined the band, Beastie Boys changed their sound, evolving from a [[hardcore punk]] band to a more hip-hop oriented group.  The band was signed to [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]], and released their debut album ''[[Licensed to Ill]]'' in 1986.  The album was a huge commercial success, and spawned six hit singles. Seven further albums followed, and by 2010 Beastie Boys had sold 22 million records in the United States alone, and 40&nbsp;million worldwide. In 2012, Beastie Boys were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].\n\nIn addition to his work with Beastie Boys, Horovitz also remixes numerous tracks for other artists under the alias 41 Small Stars.<ref>{{cite web|title=41 Small Stars|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/332355-41-Small-Stars|publisher=Discogs.com|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref> He plays bass in The Tender Moments, the backing band of New York-based [[cabaret]] performer [[Bridget Everett]].<ref name= \"bridget\">{{cite news |last=Arman |first=Marcus |url= http://www.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2012/11/30/bridget-everett-and-ad-rock-get-raunchy |title=Bridget Everett and Ad-Rock Get Raunchy |work=[[LA Weekly]] |date=2012-11-30 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nHorovitz has also acted in several motion pictures and television shows.  Some of his roles include Tim 'Chino' Doolan in ''[[Lost Angels]]'' (1989), Sam in ''[[Roadside Prophets]]'' (1992), Repulski in ''Godspeed'' (2007), Fletcher in ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]'' (2014), and Nick in ''[[Golden Exits]]'' (2017).\n\nIn 2020, he was featured in the documentary ''Have a Good Trip'' <ref>https://relix.com/news/detail/bill-kreutzmann-ad-rock-adam-scott-sarah-silverman-and-others-swap-stories-in-have-a-good-trip-adventures-in-psychedelics/ Relix</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the late 1980s, Horovitz was in a relationship with American actress [[Molly Ringwald]]. They met on the set of ''[[The Pick-up Artist (film)|The Pick-up Artist]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barshad|first1=Amos|title=Rude Boys|url=http://nymag.com/arts/popmusic/features/beastie-boys-2011-5/index4.html|accessdate=April 15, 2015|work=[[New York Magazine]]|date=April 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/the-secret-life-of-the-american-teenager/articles/molly-ringwalds-relationship-history-who-has-she-dated|title=Molly Ringwald's Relationship History: Who Has She Dated?|author=Mehera Bonner|work=Wetpaint}}</ref>\n\nHorovitz was married to actress [[Ione Skye]] from 1992 to 1995. They separated in 1995 and divorced in 1999. Since 1997 he has been involved with [[riot grrrl]] artist [[Kathleen Hanna]]; they married in 2006.<ref name=married /> Horovitz is featured prominently in ''[[The Punk Singer]]'', a 2013 documentary film about Hanna's life and career; he even shot a scene himself to show Hanna's distressed reaction to the medication she was taking against [[Lyme disease]].<ref name=EW>{{cite journal |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/03/12/sxsw-bikini-kill-kathleen-hanna-reveals-illness-in-new-doc-punk-singer/ |title=Bikini Kill's Kathleen Hanna reveals illness, reconfirms awesomeness in 'The Punk Singer' |journal=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 12, 2013 |last=Valby |first=Karen }}</ref> \n\nHorovitz began to wear a [[medical alert bracelet]] following the [[tonic\u2013clonic seizure]] he experienced in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2004/07/beastie-boys-twilight-brats/?page=1|title=Beastie Boys: Twilight of the Brats|work=Spin}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Horovitz purchased a house in [[South Pasadena, California]].<ref>